    try:
        # Try cache first
        user = await services.get_user_cached(cache, db, user_id)
        logger.debug("User retrieved", user_id=user_id, from_cache=True)
        return user
    except NotFoundError:
        logger.warning("User not found", user_id=user_id)
        raise
    except Exception as e:
        # Cache or other error - log and fallback
        logger.warning(
            "Error retrieving user, falling back to database",
            user_id=user_id,
            error=str(e),
        )
        # Fallback to direct database query
        user = await services.get_user(db, user_id)
        return user
```

## Cache Patterns Summary

### Cache-Aside (Recommended)
- ✅ Most flexible
- ✅ Works with any cache
- ✅ Easy to implement
- ⚠️ Cache miss adds latency

### Write-Through
- ✅ Cache always consistent
- ✅ Simple invalidation
- ⚠️ Slower writes
- ⚠️ More cache writes

### Write-Behind
- ✅ Fast writes
- ✅ Reduced database load
- ⚠️ Risk of data loss
- ⚠️ More complex

## Best Practices Summary

### ✅ DO
- ✅ Use cache-aside pattern for reads
- ✅ Invalidate cache on updates
- ✅ Set appropriate TTL
- ✅ Use consistent cache key format
- ✅ Handle cache errors gracefully
- ✅ Monitor cache performance
- ✅ Use type aliases for cache types
- ✅ Log cache operations
- ✅ Warm cache on startup
- ✅ Use Redis for distributed caching

### ❌ DON'T
- ❌ Don't cache sensitive data
- ❌ Don't cache forever (set TTL)
- ❌ Don't ignore cache errors
- ❌ Don't cache frequently changing data
- ❌ Don't skip invalidation
- ❌ Don't use inconsistent key formats
- ❌ Don't cache large objects
- ❌ Don't cache without monitoring
